PKI ‚Äì Session 8 is core PKI theory and very frequently asked in CCEE.
Most questions come from CA role, trust models, certificate lifecycle, CRL vs OCSP, and certificate types.

Below is a DITISS-aligned, CCEE-focused MCQ set.

üìò Public Key Infrastructure ‚Äì Session 8
CA, Trust Models, Certificate Lifecycle
(PG-DITISS August 2025)

üü¢ BASIC MCQs (10)
1. CA stands for:
A. Cryptographic Authority
B. Certificate Authority
C. Central Authority
D. Certified Authority

2. The main role of a Certificate Authority is to:
A. Encrypt data
B. Generate hashes
C. Issue digital certificates
D. Store passwords

3. A digital certificate is issued after:
A. Key encryption
B. Identity verification
C. Hash generation
D. Data compression

4. Which entity signs a digital certificate?
A. User
B. Server
C. Certificate Authority
D. Browser

5. Trust in PKI is based on:
A. Symmetric keys
B. Root certificate
C. Hash value
D. Firewall rules

6. Certificate Revocation means:
A. Certificate expiry
B. Temporary suspension
C. Invalidating a certificate before expiry
D. Renewing certificate

7. CRL stands for:
A. Certificate Renewal List
B. Certificate Revocation List
C. Certified Root List
D. Cryptographic Revocation Log

8. OCSP is a:
A. Protocol
B. Algorithm
C. Hash function
D. Encryption method

9. Root CA certificate is usually:
A. Issued by Intermediate CA
B. Self-signed
C. Expired
D. Revoked

10. Which certificate is issued to end users or servers?
A. Root certificate
B. Intermediate certificate
C. End-entity certificate
D. Cross certificate

üî∏ INTERMEDIATE MCQs (10)
11. Trust model where one root CA is trusted by all entities is:
A. Web of Trust
B. Hierarchical trust
C. Mesh trust
D. Bridge trust

12. In a hierarchical trust model:
A. No root CA exists
B. Multiple independent roots
C. Root CA is at the top
D. All CAs are equal

13. Which trust model is used in PGP?
A. Hierarchical
B. Bridge
C. Web of Trust
D. Centralized

14. Certificate issuance process starts with:
A. Certificate signing
B. CSR creation
C. Certificate installation
D. Revocation

15. CSR stands for:
A. Certificate Security Request
B. Certificate Signing Request
C. Certified Server Request
D. Cryptographic Signing Record

16. Which information is included in a CSR?
A. Private key
B. Public key
C. Symmetric key
D. Hash only

17. Which method checks certificate status in real time?
A. CRL
B. OCSP
C. CSR
D. CA hierarchy

18. CRL drawback is:
A. High computation
B. Large size & delay
C. No security
D. Key exposure

19. OCSP response is provided by:
A. Client
B. Server
C. OCSP Responder
D. Firewall

20. Which certificate is used to sign other certificates?
A. End-entity
B. Client certificate
C. CA certificate
D. Email certificate

üî∫ ADVANCED MCQs (10)
21. Bridge trust model is mainly used to:
A. Replace root CA
B. Connect multiple PKI hierarchies
C. Encrypt data faster
D. Reduce certificate size

22. If a root CA is compromised, impact is:
A. Only one certificate affected
B. Only intermediate CA affected
C. Entire PKI trust collapses
D. No impact

23. Certificate lifecycle includes all EXCEPT:
A. Issuance
B. Validation
C. Revocation
D. Encryption

24. OCSP stapling improves:
A. Encryption strength
B. Certificate issuance
C. Performance & privacy
D. Key size

25. Which certificate class is used for SSL/TLS websites?
A. Code signing certificate
B. Email certificate
C. Server certificate
D. Root certificate

26. Extended Validation (EV) certificates provide:
A. Stronger encryption
B. Higher trust level
C. Larger key size
D. Faster connection

27. Which certificate type is used to sign software?
A. Client certificate
B. Server certificate
C. Code signing certificate
D. Root certificate

28. Cross-certification helps in:
A. Certificate revocation
B. Trust between different CAs
C. Faster hashing
D. Key generation

29. Which component maintains CRL?
A. Client
B. Server
C. Certificate Authority
D. Browser

30. CCEE TRAP in Session 8 usually tests:
A. CRL vs OCSP difference
B. Trust model identification
C. Certificate type usage
D. All of the above

‚úÖ ANSWER KEY
Basic:
1.B | 2.C | 3.B | 4.C | 5.B | 6.C | 7.B | 8.A | 9.B | 10.C

Intermediate:
11.B | 12.C | 13.C | 14.B | 15.B | 16.B | 17.B | 18.B | 19.C | 20.C

Advanced:
21.B | 22.C | 23.D | 24.C | 25.C | 26.B | 27.C | 28.B | 29.C | 30.D

üéØ CCEE QUICK REVISION (SESSION 8)
CA = issues & manages certificates
Root CA = self-signed
CSR contains public key
CRL = offline, OCSP = real-time
Hierarchical trust = most common
EV certificates = higher validation
